        ]
      ],
      "content": "A translucent figure stands at the centre of the star chart, gazing down at the silver constellations beneath its feet. It wears the robes of a scholar and holds a quill that leaves no mark. Its edges shimmer like heat haze."
    },
    {
      "kind": 30078,
      "tags": [
        [
          "d",
          "cartographers-instrument:dialogue:cartographer:greeting"
        ],
        [
          "t",
          "cartographers-instrument"
        ],
        [
          "type",
          "dialogue"
        ],
        [
          "option",
          "What is this place?",
          "30078:<PUBKEY>:cartographers-instrument:dialogue:cartographer:place"
        ],
        [
          "option",
          "What happened here?",
          "30078:<PUBKEY>:cartographers-instrument:dialogue:cartographer:history"
        ],
        [
          "option",
          "How do I use the instrument?",
          "30078:<PUBKEY>:cartographers-instrument:dialogue:cartographer:instrument"
        ],
        [
          "option",
          "Leave",
          ""
        ]
      ],
      "content": "The figure turns toward you. Its eyes are points of white light.\n\n*You found it. The instrument. I wondered if anyone ever would.*"
    },
    {
      "kind": 30078,
      "tags": [
        [
          "d",
          "cartographers-instrument:dialogue:cartographer:place"
        ],
        [
          "t",
          "cartographers-instrument"
        ],
        [
          "type",
          "dialogue"
        ],
        [
          "option",
          "Tell me about the resonators",
          "30078:<PUBKEY>:cartographers-instrument:dialogue:cartographer:resonators"
        ],
        [
          "option",
          "Leave",
          ""
        ]
      ],
      "content": "*An observatory. But not for seeing — for listening. I mapped the music of the spheres. Each room remembers its note. The composition was almost complete when I... well. When I stopped being able to hold the instrument.*"
    },
    {
      "kind": 30078,
      "tags": [
        [
          "d",
          "cartographers-instrument:dialogue:cartographer:history"
        ],
        [
          "t",
          "cartographers-instrument"
        ],
        [
          "type",
          "dialogue"
        ],
        [
          "option",
          "Tell me about the resonators",
          "30078:<PUBKEY>:cartographers-instrument:dialogue:cartographer:resonators"
        ],
        [
          "option",
          "Leave",
          ""
        ]
      ],
      "content": "*I spent a lifetime charting the celestial harmonics. Three rooms, three notes, three resonators tuned to the music that holds the sky together. I built the instrument to play them. But the composition requires living hands. Mine are... somewhat lacking in that regard now.*"
    },
    {
      "kind": 30078,
      "tags": [
        [
          "d",
          "cartographers-instrument:dialogue:cartographer:instrument"
        ],
        [
          "t",
          "cartographers-instrument"
        ],
        [
          "type",
          "dialogue"
        ],
        [
          "option",
          "Tell me about the resonators",
          "30078:<PUBKEY>:cartographers-instrument:dialogue:cartographer:resonators"
        ],
        [
          "option",
          "Leave",
          ""
        ]
      ],
      "content": "*Take it to each resonator. The charts on the walls will tell you which note belongs where. Play them in any order — the composition will find itself. When all three sing together, the Star Chamber will open.*"
    },
    {
      "kind": 30078,
      "tags": [
        [
          "d",
          "cartographers-instrument:dialogue:cartographer:resonators"
        ],
        [
          "t",
          "cartographers-instrument"
        ],
        [
          "type",
          "dialogue"
        ],
        [
          "option",
          "Thank you",
          ""
        ]
      ],
      "content": "*Three resonators. The Lunar, to the west — it sounds the root, the foundation of all harmony. The Solar, to the east — the fifth, bright and reaching. And the Stellar, above — the third, the bridge between. Together they form a chord that the ancients believed was the sound of creation itself. The tower will not open until the moon and sun are singing. You must wake them first.*"
    },
